            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Megan Ito's story didn't begin in San Francisco, but it was forged there. Raised in Modesto, she grew up Megan Miller, a practical girl from a working-class family who had a flair for the artistic but no patience for academia. While her friends obsessed over college applications, Megan was perfecting intricate designs on press-on nails, finding a meditative focus in the tiny, detailed work. After high school, she enrolled in cosmetology school, quickly realizing her passion was not in hair, but in the miniature canvases of fingernails.\n\nHer move to San Francisco at 21 was an act of love. She followed her then-husband, Kenji Ito, a promising graphic designer. The city was a kaleidoscope of new experiences, and Megan, now Megan Ito, felt she could finally breathe. She landed a job at a bustling Union Square salon, her talent for complex, hand-painted nail art setting her apart. While her marriage to Kenji eventually ended amicably after a decade\u2014they had simply grown into different people\u2014she kept the name. It felt like a part of the identity she had built for herself in the city.\n\nNow 40, Megan is the Lead Nail Technician at a chic, minimalist salon in Hayes Valley. She is the artist-in-residence, the one clients book months in advance for her steady hand and creative vision. Her days are a rhythm of practiced motions and quiet conversations, making her a trusted confidante to a cross-section of San Francisco\u2019s populace.\n\nHer life is contained and curated. She lives in a small, rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond, a neighborhood she loves for its foggy mornings and proximity to Golden Gate Park. Her 3.8-mile commute on the 38 Geary bus is her time to decompress, listening to true-crime podcasts as the city slides by. Her social life is a tight-knit circle of fellow stylists and a few loyal clients who have become genuine friends.\n\nMegan\u2019s dream is quiet but persistent: to own her own small, appointment-only nail studio. A serene, two-chair space where she can control the atmosphere, mentor a promising new artist, and continue her craft on her own terms. It\u2019s not about getting rich; it\u2019s about ownership and creating a lasting piece of beauty in the city that allowed her to become herself."
